Pour 300ml cold salted water (double for 4p) into a #medium pot{} with a
tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @rice{150%g} and bring to the boil.

Once boiling, lower the heat to medium, cover, and cook for ~{10%minutes}.

Remove the pot from the heat.

Keep covered for ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will
continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @shallot{1}.

Trim the @green beans{75%g} then chop into thirds.

Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Roughly chop the @coriander{5%g}(roughly chopped) (stalks and all).

Place a #large pan{} over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Add the @Diced Irish Chicken Breast{260%g} and season with @salt{to taste} and
@pepper{to taste}.

Cook until the chicken is browned, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Once the chicken is browned, add the shallot and cook until softened,
stirring frequently, ~{3-4%minutes}.

> TIP: Notice a stronger smell from your chicken? Don't worry, this is
> normal due to packaging used to keep it fresh.

Add the garlic and @curry powder{2%sachets} and stir to coat the chicken.
Cook for ~{1%minute}.

Pour in 100ml water (double for 4p) along with the @chicken stock{1%sachet}.

Add the green beans, bring to the boil, then reduce the heat to medium.
Cover the pan with a lid or some #foil{}.

Simmer until the green beans are tender, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Once the green beans are tender and the chicken is cooked, remove the lid and
stir in the @creme fraiche{110%g} and @cranberry chutney{1%sachet}.

> IMPORTANT: Chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Bring to the boil, then remove from the heat. Stir in half the coriander.

Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and divide between bowls.

Top with the chicken curry.

Finish with a sprinkling of the remaining coriander.